Flexible cFDR: Related trait simulations

We want to make sure that our simulations representing iterating over related traits (simulations B) are as realistic as possible.

  • To investigate how correlated \(p\)-values tend to be for related traits in real data sets, I extracted GWAS \(p\)-values for T1D (Cooper et al.2017) and related traits: RA (Ishigaki et al.2020), UC (DeLange et al.2017), CD (DeLange et al.2017), PSC (Ji et al.2017), PBD (Cordell et al.2015) and CEL (Trynka et al.2011). I also extracted GWAS \(p\)-values for T2D (Mahajan et al.2018) to use as a negative control. I removed chromosome 6 so extremely significant \(p\)-values in the MHC do not bias the results.

  • I also have the correlations from Toms PID analysis. This includes, PID (principal trait), allergy phenotype, asthma, UC, CD, SLE, RA, T1D, T2D and CAD.

Correlations between related traits with eachother

Firstly, I compare the correlations between related traits (i.e.removing the principal trait) in both of these real-data analyses for raw p-values and log-transformed p-values. The correlation between T1D and T2D p-values is shown in blue.

I also show the distribution of the correlations from my simulations. Share X refers to how many LD blocks are simulated to share causal variants. Share 4 is what we were using originally, but it looks like Share 1 may be more realistic.

Observations:

  • Even only specifying shared causal variants in 1 out of 24 LD blocks gives correlations that are higher than that seen in real data.

  • In my simulations, sometimes the correlation between related traits is negative. If they are also negative with the principal trait then this is ok in Flexible cFDR as the software flips the sign of the auxiliary data values, but empirical cFDR does not have such a feature.

Corrrelations between principal trait and related traits

Between the principal trait and each related trait, we originally specified 4 blocks to share CVs which gave a correlation of 0.06, I tried reducing this to 3 shared blocks and then 2 shared blocks. [Note I couldnt include Toms correlations here because Ive only got correlations for everything not-logged or everything logged].

So I now have results from my original simulations (4 shared blocks between each related trait and the principal trait, and between each related trait; in red blow) and my new simulations (2 shared blocks between each related trait and the principal trait, and 1 shared block between each related trait; in blue below). Simulation results

Empirical cFDR seems to decrease in sensitivity in these new simulations (related traits have 2 shared blocks with principal trait and 1 with eachother).. maybe because some of the correlations are negative and whereas Flexible cFDR would automatically flip the sign of \(q\) in these instances, empirical does not?

We could also define an extra parameter in the software relating to the left censoring step. We currently have a parameter called gridp for how many data points are required in a grid space of the KDE to trust the KDE (default value of 50) whereby anything in the left tail with fewer data points than this was left censored. We could add an additional left censoring parameter where users can instead define a threshold for left censoring if they so wish. One, but not both, of these parameters should be set to NULL.

A lot of values are left censored in my related trait simulations because the gridp parameter is used with default settings. It would be good to investigate the left censoring in a more realistically sized GWAS. I could extend my simulations for all chromosomes, but this will require UK10K haplotype data for LD blocks and LD matrices (for simGWAS). Tom is running his analysis and storing how many data points are left-censored.

T1D GWAS

We have non-QCed data in plink format for 3 data sets: ORPS (200 samples), AdDIT (1363 samples) and OXFORD (708 novel samples sequenced by Thermo Fisher using the Axiom UKBB V2 array). The ORPS and AdDIT data is present in two separate directories: GWASdata from UVA2016 and GWASdata from USB_NeilWalker. The former is imputed, QCed data but the latter contains the raw data. I propose that we use the raw data and follow our own QC and imputation protocol. I plan to use Snakemake for this project (useful for Snakemake automation of GWAS QC: https://github.com/pmonnahan/DataPrep).

QC

This will be useful: https://github.com/MareesAT/GWA_tutorial

Sample QC:

  • Remove sample mislabeled as male/female (if sex is missing but can be inferred, use this).
  • Remove samples with \(>5%\) missingness.
  • Remove samples with extreme heterozygosity values (plot heterozygosity f statistic and determine a threshold value; https://discuss.hail.is/t/filtering-samples-with-extreme-heterozygosity-in-hail/1277).
  • Filter out related samples (IBS).
  • Extract non-European samples and store these seperately.

SNP QC:

  • Remove SNPs with \(>5%\) missingness.
  • Remove low frequency SNPs (\(<0.01\); but maybe this is too stringent for small sample sizes, e.g.ORPS).
  • Remove SNPs deviating from HWE (need to discuss threshold).
  • Remove heterozygous haploid SNPs (that remain after creating Chr 25).

[Note that I can compare our QC results for ORPS and AdDIT with those using Ranys script].

Imputation

Use Will Rayners script for data preparation. This produces a set of plink commands to remove problematic palindromic SNPs, remove SNPs with differing alleles, remove SNPs with \(>0.2\) allele frequency difference between GWAS data and reference panel (this value can be adjusted) and remove SNPs not in reference panel. It then updates SNPs by strands, alleles, positions and Ref/Alt assignment.

Use Michigan Imputation Server to impute using HRC reference panel (monomorphic SNPs are lost at this point but we can add these back in later).

Use Will Rayners IC software for post-imputation checking.
